metadata.name: Whisper #264
metadata.description:
Abstract forms built with noise and texture

-------------

A note on rendering times: *Whisper has a lot going on*. It can take up to 1-5 minutes to fully render, depending on your hardware configuration, including a 15sec-1min loading phase during which lots of calculations take place (but no visuals). It'll get there, just be patient! A small loading bar along the bottom also shows the progression of the render during the drawing phase.

Press 'S' or click "Save image" to save a PNG version of the artwork while in full-screen/IPFS view

Customisation
-------------

The following parameters can be adjusted in full-screen mode.
Open the token in full-screen/IPFS mode, and add any of these to the URL:

&size=2000 (replace 2000 with any value up to around 8000) - this sets the resolution/width of the canvas in pixels. Use this to generate very large PNG images (50MB+) suitable for printing at large DPI & canvas sizes. The max value here is dependent on your hardware, might not work on mobiles etc.

&ratio=1.4 (any value between 1 and 2, default = 1.4) - set the aspect ratio of the work. By default Whisper renders at 1:1.4 but you can change this to match other printing formats. Different ratios will produce slightly different outputs, but the overall character of the artwork should still be present. Landscape mode is not supported.

metadata.name: simple things #95
metadata.description:
There’s beauty in simple things. Sunlight. A reflection on a puddle. The flight of a bird. Observing the clouds. Spending time with loved ones.

To celebrate the re-opening of fxhash, I'd like to contribute with some simple thing to enjoy among friends who rejoin after some time.

Simple things is a piece that is just that: simple things. Nothing fancy here. Simple circles doing simple movement, with simple colours. Maybe the viewer will rejoice in observing them transit on the screen.

It has some controls: you can press “s” to save a png file. You can set a higher resolution pressing “d” followed by 1-9 to increase pixel density (if you get a black image, press “d 0” and start again with a lower number). Simple controls.

It has also colour controls: press z for brightness, x for contrast, g for gamma, b for blur, n for noise followed by + or - to alter their values. You might get some simple variations that you might enjoy. Press a to enable/disable all colour controls (except the noise).

The pieces exhibit simple variations: palettes, circle sizes, density of elements, backgrounds. The colours might be inverted sometimes. The direction of the movement changes also in some pieces. Some are grayscale pieces.

Just like in life, enjoying simple things is sometimes enough to leave behind the noise and our worries. Also like in life, if one wants something extra, they may get it by looking for it...

Artwork by Marcelo Soria-Rodríguez, @msoriaro.
Made in p5.js, and glsl for the image controls.

metadata.name: pang #21
metadata.description:
Within each of us resides an evolutionary history of primal emotions, yet we often spend our lives dulling and controlling these instincts rather than reveling in them. Art is one of the ways we best express those instincts and intuitions – accessing and visualizing their visceral qualities, and releasing our deepest emotions in a way we can share.

pang reflects emotions that take control of our impulses – anguish, euphoria, obsession. By using crayon-like marks, the artworks convey the catharsis felt while drawing with a childlike abandon. To capture what gives such marks true feeling, the works deliberate the intrinsic movements, pressures, and angles shaped by hands in various moods. These qualities and their frenetic meanderings represent the infinite possibilities of where the crayon could go next – if only we could free ourselves from the layers of control we've built.

The contradictions we struggle with are reflected throughout the works:  in the long, methodical, and mathematical path to creation that yields work that looks fast, free and unrehearsed;  through the randomly-informed computer generation of art that feels human;  and by the depiction of long-standing traditional techniques to help display the conceptual range of a young, innovative art movement still establishing its pivotal place in the canon of art. These tensions parallel the work's underlying concept, accentuating the suspicion that a learned fear of emotional expression might just be the source of our own pang. 

Created in p5.js, pang is inspired by the emotional works and processes of later abstract expressionists such as Cy Twombly and Joan Mitchell – as well as contemporary artists like José Parla.

Functionality: 
Press ‘p’ to save as a png. 
Press ‘b’ to render with (or without) a transparent background.
Press 0-9 to render at varying degrees of quality.  0 (lowest quality) to 9 (highest quality, 15000 pixels lengthwise).
Press ⬆️ (arrow up) to incrementally increase pixel density.
Press ⬇️ (arrow down) to incrementally decrease pixel density.

__________
TENDER x abstractment
April 2022

metadata.name: Suspension #23
metadata.description:
Suspension uses simple objects to create structures suspended in space, held together by relation and composition.

The unique composition algorithm is random enough to produce infinite variations, but ordered enough to produce engaging artworks that are instantly recognizable.

Suspension uses negative space, additive coloring, and a unique rendering technique to create a very distinct style. 

It has many hand tuned palettes, with rare palettes that produce incisive variations.

Suspension is responsive and will render fast at any resolution. It looks great on wide screens of 2K, 4K or larger.

To accommodate the variation in displays, you can use the up/down arrow keys to adjust the brightness. 'r' resets to the default values.

's' will save an image in the exact size of the window, so you can create images in any resolution.

metadata.name: Artificial Flower 2 (2022), walkers series #6
metadata.description:
The first version was made at 2016 year. That time I was experiment with random walkers. The idea behind this sketch is the same with some my other artworks: create visual complex result with the basic rules that sometimes has references to the classic generative art technics by repeating a lot of iterations and mixing that classic technics with new possibilities that p5js brings – currently for that sketch is "random walker" technics and p5js color mixing and change alpha channel.

The first name of this sketch was "Painter walk" but I'm think that it's more looks like a flower, Artificial Flower.

Randomisation based on hash:
1. Color1 and Color2, that randomly selected from the list of 10 colors. If Color1 and Color2 can't be the same color, but sometimes it can be the darker or lighter version of the same color may create 3D effect (alpha also make such effect).
2. Amount of walkers (lines)
3. Each walker has uniq size, lifespan and walk path
4. I hope that I didn't forgot to mention something that also use fxhash randomisation.

The v1 can be found at https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/4439

I hope you will like it. Soon I will publish more new sketches and than adapt and publish my old sketches that was made in period from 2012 to 2019 year. Some of artworks from my profile are new. This one is remake of my old sketch that was made in 2016.

Thanks.

metadata.name: Edouard Manet #11
metadata.description:
Edouard Manet  was a French modernist painter. He was one of the first 19th-century artists to paint modern life, as well as a pivotal figure in the transition from Realism to Impressionism.

His early masterworks, The Luncheon on the Grass and Olympia, both 1863, caused great controversy and served as rallying points for the young painters who would create Impressionism. Today, these are considered watershed paintings that mark the start of modern art.

Although harshly condemned by critics who decried its lack of conventional finish, Manets work had admirers from the beginning. One was Emile Zola, who wrote in 1867: "We are not accustomed to seeing such simple and direct translations of reality. Then, as I said, there is such a surprisingly elegant awkwardness ... it is a truly charming experience to contemplate this luminous and serious painting which interprets nature with a gentle brutality."
